[[Lieutenant General]] '''Sir William Sherbrooke Ramsey Norcott''' <small>[[Order of the Bath|KCB]]</small> (12 December 1804 &ndash; 23 January 1886) of the [[Rifle Brigade (Prince Consort's Own)|Rifle Brigade]] was a [[British Army]] officer who fought during the [[Crimean War]], was an [[Aide-de-Camp]] to [[Queen Victoria]] and became [[Lieutenant Governor of Jersey]].

==Early life==
William Norcott was born on 12 December 1804 in [[Chelmsford]] [[Essex]], the second son to [[General (United Kingdom)|General]] Sir [[Amos Norcott|Amos Godsell Robert Norcott]] <small>[[Order of the Bath|CB]] [[Royal Guelphic Order|KCH]]</small> who had commanded a [[Battalion#British Army|battalion]] of the [[Rifle Brigade (Prince Consort's Own)|95th Rifles]] at the [[Battle of Waterloo]].<ref name=reillyrelations>[https://archive.org/stream/historyofmaunsel00maun/historyofmaunsel00maun_djvu.txt Internet Archive]</ref>

==Military career==
Norcott was [[Commissioned officer|commissioned]] into the [[Rifle Brigade (Prince Consort's Own)|Rifle Brigade]] in 1822<ref name=bio>[http://www.corkpastandpresent.ie/places/northcork/grovewhitenotes/shinanaghtowoodville/gw4_221_234.pdf Cork past and present]</ref> and made a [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] of the [[52nd (Oxfordshire) Regiment of Foot|52nd Regiment]] in on 21 February 1840.<ref name=familyunearthed>[http://www.familiesunearthed.com/reilly/norcott/william-sherbrooke-ramsay.htm familiesunearthed.com]</ref>  Later the same year (7 August) he returned to the Rifles and on 1 August 1847 became a [[Major (United Kingdom)|Major]].

During the [[Crimean War]] he fought at the [[Battle of Alma]] and commanded 1st Battalion, the Rifle Brigade at the [[Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855)|Siege of Sevastopol]].<ref name=bio/>

Between 1855 and 1868 he was [[Aide-de-Camp]] to [[Queen Victoria]],<ref name=familyunearthed /> then went on to become [[Lieutenant Governor of Jersey]] between 1 October 1873 to 30 September 1878.<ref name=familyunearthed />

He was awarded the [[Order of the Bath|Knight of the Order of the Bath]] in 1877 and became a [[General (United Kingdom)|General]] in 1879.<ref name=familyunearthed />

==Later Years==

After his retirement he wrote some letters to [[The Times]] newspaper disputing some of the claims made about the battle of Alma.<ref>[http://crimeantexts.russianwar.co.uk/sources/times/t630320b.html crimeantexts 1]</ref><ref>[http://www.crimeantexts.org.uk/sources/times/t630325a.html crimeantexts 2]</ref>

William died at 87 on 23 January 1886 in [[St. Leonard's-on-Sea]], [[Sussex]].

==Family==
In 1848 he married Frances Marrianne Durant; they had six children,<ref name=reillyrelations /> at least 3 sons became soldiers.

*[[Charles Norcott|Charles Hawtrey Bruce Norcott]] born 25 April 1849 became a General of the Rifle Brigade.
*Walter Gordon Norcott born about 1851, became a [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-colonel]] in the [[Royal Munster Fusiliers]] (also served in the [[101st Regiment of Foot (Royal Bengal Fusiliers)|Royal Bengal Fusiliers]])<ref>[http://archiver.rootsweb.ancestry.com/th/read/INDIA/1999-05/0926672540 rootsweb.com]</ref><ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/30831/supplements/9302/page.pdf London Gazette Aug.1918]</ref>
*Gerald Alfred born about 1861 became a Major of the [[Loyal Regiment (North Lancashire)]] (having originally joined the [[47th (Lancashire) Regiment of Foot|47th Foot]] and who died of [[Pneumonia]] whilst on staff service during World War I.<ref>[http://www.greatwarci.net/honour/jersey/database/norcott-ga-newcastle.htm greatwarci.net]</ref>

